<section class="hero">
  <h1>Does Bitcoin Earn Its <em>Place?</em></h1>
  <div class="hero-subtitle">A preceding exploration, How Much Bitcoin, finds the optimal fraction. This one answers a plainer question: over a long horizon, does adding bitcoin actually make your portfolio better, drawdowns and all?</div>
  <p class="subtitle">Set bitcoin as a percentage of your whole portfolio and get the answer with its cost in the same breath: the extra return over a long hold, the drawdown you would have to sit through, and the share of your portfolio&rsquo;s ongoing risk bitcoin drives. Grounded, sourced defaults, so you are not guessing at the numbers.</p>
</section>

<main class="content-area">

  {% include 'components/tool-framing.njk' %}

  <!-- ════════ INTRO ════════ -->
  <div class="section-intro as-prose">
    <p><a href="/how-much-bitcoin">How Much Bitcoin?</a> answers <em>what fraction is optimal</em>, the Kelly maths of sizing. This page answers the question a cautious investor asks first: is bitcoin worth adding at all, once you account for the crashes? You hold bitcoin as a percentage of a normal portfolio, the rest in a broad-market sleeve, and over a long horizon the answer has usually been yes, a modest allocation adds more return than its drawdown costs. But that is only useful if the reasons for it are stated plainly, and if the cost is stated just as plainly.</p>
    <p>So the answer here always comes with its price. Every gain sits beside the drawdown you would have to hold through and the share of your risk bitcoin drives. Those last two are easy to confuse, so keep them apart: the drawdown is how far your portfolio falls in a crash, a one-time hit; the risk contribution is how much of your portfolio&rsquo;s ongoing volatility bitcoin drives, a structural share. A 10% position is about a quarter of your risk on that second measure. The page shows the consequences of a choice; it does not tell you which choice to make.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ════════ ABOVE THE FOLD: allocation + verdict + effects ════════ -->
  <section class="as-section as-lab" id="worth-it">
    <div class="as-eyebrow">Is it worth it?</div>
    <h2 class="as-h2">Set the allocation, read the answer</h2>

    <div class="as-primary">
      <div class="as-primary-head">
        <span class="as-primary-label">Bitcoin allocation
          <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Bitcoin as a share of your whole portfolio. The rest sits in a broad-market sleeve. This is the one lever the whole page turns on; the assumptions below are set once.</span></span>
        </span>
        <span class="as-primary-val"><input type="number" id="asAlloc" min="0" max="100" step="1" aria-label="Bitcoin allocation percent"><span class="as-primary-suffix">%</span></span>
      </div>
      <input type="range" id="asAllocSlider" class="as-range" min="0" max="100" step="1" aria-label="Bitcoin allocation slider">
      <div class="as-seg as-seg-mini as-presets" id="asAllocPresets">
        <button type="button" data-val="1">1%</button>
        <button type="button" data-val="5">5%</button>
        <button type="button" data-val="10">10%</button>
        <button type="button" data-val="20">20%</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="as-verdict as-verdict-yes" id="asVerdict">&mdash;</div>

    <div class="as-faces">
      <div class="as-face as-face-up" id="faceUpside">
        <div class="as-face-eyebrow">Extra return</div>
        <div class="as-face-num">&mdash;</div>
        <div class="as-face-unit">&mdash;</div>
        <p class="as-face-detail">&mdash;</p>
      </div>
      <div class="as-face as-face-down" id="faceDrawdown">
        <div class="as-face-eyebrow">Drawdown</div>
        <div class="as-face-num">&mdash;</div>
        <div class="as-face-unit">&mdash;</div>
        <p class="as-face-detail">&mdash;</p>
      </div>
      <div class="as-face as-face-risk" id="faceRisk">
        <div class="as-face-eyebrow">Risk contribution</div>
        <div class="as-face-num">&mdash;</div>
        <div class="as-face-unit">&mdash;</div>
        <p class="as-face-detail">&mdash;</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="as-faces-note">The <strong>drawdown</strong> and the <strong>risk contribution</strong> are different things: the drawdown is a one-time fall in a crash, the risk contribution is bitcoin&rsquo;s share of the everyday swings. Both are the cost side of the answer above.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ THE ASSUMPTIONS (calm secondary block) ════════ -->
  <section class="as-section" id="assumptions">
    <div class="as-eyebrow">The assumptions</div>
    <h2 class="as-h2">What we assume, and why</h2>
    <p class="as-lead">Set once, then leave. These are grounded, sourced defaults so the answer above rests on something, not a blank guess. Change any of them if your own expectation differs.</p>
    <div class="as-controls">
      <div class="as-control">
        <div class="as-control-label">Time horizon
          <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">How long you hold. Bitcoin is a long-horizon allocation: it has no negative five-year hold on record, and the case weakens under about five years.</span></span>
          <span class="as-control-val" id="asHorizonVal">10 years</span>
        </div>
        <input type="range" id="asHorizon" class="as-range" min="1" max="30" step="1" aria-label="Time horizon in years">
        <p class="as-control-note">Every rolling twenty-year stock period since 1928 was positive; bitcoin&rsquo;s worst five-year holds were not. This is a long game.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="as-control">
        <div class="as-control-label">Bitcoin grows
          <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">A forward rate, not a moonshot. Tempered toward the Power Law and to VanEck&rsquo;s base case (~15%/yr), well below bitcoin&rsquo;s history. Shown as the multiple it compounds to over the hold.</span></span>
          <span class="as-control-val" id="asBtcRateVal">15%/yr &rarr; 4.05x</span>
        </div>
        <input type="range" id="asBtcRate" class="as-range as-range-red" min="0" max="30" step="1" aria-label="Bitcoin annual rate">
        <p class="as-control-note">A Power-Law-tempered forward rate, well below bitcoin&rsquo;s past. See <a href="/bull-and-bear-cycles">Bull &amp; Bear Cycles</a>.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="as-control">
        <div class="as-control-label">The rest grows
          <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Your broad-market sleeve. Default ~10%/yr, roughly the S&amp;P&rsquo;s long-run nominal return. Lower it toward ~7% for a conservative, more real-terms figure.</span></span>
          <span class="as-control-val" id="asTradRateVal">10%/yr &rarr; 2.59x</span>
        </div>
        <input type="range" id="asTradRate" class="as-range" min="0" max="15" step="1" aria-label="Traditional sleeve annual rate">
        <p class="as-control-note">Roughly the S&amp;P&rsquo;s long-run nominal return. The baseline bitcoin is measured against.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="as-control">
        <div class="as-control-label">Crash depth
          <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">How far bitcoin falls peak-to-trough in a bear market, for the drawdown figure. Your choice, not a prediction. &minus;77% is bitcoin&rsquo;s historical characteristic.</span></span>
          <span class="as-control-val" id="asDepthVal">&minus;77%</span>
        </div>
        <input type="range" id="asDepthSlider" class="as-range as-range-red" min="20" max="90" step="1" aria-label="Crash depth percent">
        <div class="as-seg as-seg-mini" id="asDepth">
          <button type="button" data-val="40">&minus;40%</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="60">&minus;60%</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="77">&minus;77%</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="as-control">
        <div class="as-field">
          <span>Total portfolio (optional)
            <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Enter a dollar amount to see the extra return and the drawdown as real dollars. Leave blank to stay in multiples and percentages.</span></span>
          </span>
          <input type="text" inputmode="numeric" id="asPortfolio" placeholder="e.g. 500,000" aria-label="Total portfolio in dollars">
          <p class="as-field-note">Optional. Turns the answer into dollars.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="as-assumptions" id="asAssumptions">&mdash;</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ THE COMPARISON ════════ -->
  <section class="as-section" id="compare">
    <div class="as-eyebrow">The comparison</div>
    <h2 class="as-h2">The shape of the trade-off</h2>
    <p class="as-lead">Several allocations side by side, so you see the shape rather than one point. As the position grows, the extra return rises, but the drawdown and the risk contribution rise faster. That divergence is why sizing is deliberate.</p>
    <div class="as-compare-grid">
      <div class="as-chart-wrap"><canvas id="asCompareChart"></canvas></div>
      <div class="as-tablewrap">
        <table class="as-table">
          <thead id="asCompareHead"><tr><th>Allocation</th><th class="as-num">Portfolio</th><th class="as-num">Extra return</th><th class="as-num">Drawdown</th><th class="as-num">Risk share</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody id="asCompareBody"></tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="as-chart-caption">Each group is a separate allocation, not one portfolio over time. <strong style="color:#6fae6f">Extra return</strong> is how much more your portfolio grows than with no bitcoin over the hold; <strong style="color:#e08a7a">drawdown</strong> is the one-time whole-portfolio hit in the chosen bear; <strong style="color:#e09422">risk contribution</strong> is bitcoin&rsquo;s share of your ongoing risk. The upside is always plotted next to its costs.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ REBALANCING TEMPTATION ════════ -->
  <section class="as-section" id="after">
    <div class="as-eyebrow">After you choose</div>
    <h2 class="as-h2">The position does not stay put</h2>
    <p class="as-rebalance" id="asRebalance">&mdash;</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ CAN YOU HOLD IT ════════ -->
  <section class="as-section" id="hold">
    <div class="as-eyebrow">Can you hold it?</div>
    <h2 class="as-h2">The number you have to live through</h2>
    <p class="as-hold" id="asHold">&mdash;</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ AUDIT ════════ -->
  <section class="as-section" id="audit">
    <button class="as-audit-toggle" id="asAuditToggle" aria-expanded="false">
      <span class="as-audit-label">Verify the math</span>
      <span class="as-audit-hint">extra return, drawdown, and risk contribution for each allocation, computed from the stated assumptions.</span>
    </button>
    <div id="asAuditBody2" hidden>
      <div class="as-audit-actions">
        <button type="button" class="as-csv-btn" id="asCsvBtn"><span class="as-csv-label">Download CSV</span></button>
      </div>
      <div class="as-tablewrap">
        <table class="as-table">
          <thead id="asAuditHead"><tr><th>Allocation</th><th class="as-num">Portfolio upside</th><th class="as-num">Extra return</th><th class="as-num">Drawdown</th><th class="as-num">Risk share</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody id="asAuditBody"></tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="as-chart-caption">Portfolio upside is the weighted single-hold multiple from the horizon and the two growth rates. Extra return is that against the no-bitcoin multiple. Drawdown is the allocation times the crash depth. Risk contribution is bitcoin&rsquo;s share of total portfolio variance, given bitcoin volatility 45%, the sleeve 12%, and a 0.50 correlation, and matches the published reference points (a 10% position is about a quarter of risk).</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ WHERE THIS CONNECTS ════════ -->
  <section class="as-section" id="connects">
    <div class="as-eyebrow">Where this connects</div>
    <h2 class="as-h2">The rest of the chain</h2>
    <div class="as-prose as-prose-wide">
      <p>This page owns the accumulation-era allocation choice: whether a bitcoin position earns its place while you are building it, and what it does for and to a portfolio over a long hold. It does not tell you the number to pick. The optimal fraction is a maths problem, and it lives on How Much Bitcoin. What a position does later, once you are drawing an income from it, lives on the Retirement pages. And whether to trim a winning position back to target, once bitcoin has grown past where you started it, is the open question Disciplined Rebalancing works through.</p>
      <p>One note on the assumptions: bitcoin&rsquo;s diversification benefit has weakened since the ETFs arrived, with its correlation to traditional markets running higher than it once did. This page keeps the correlation on the high side for that reason, so it does not overstate the free-diversification case.</p>
    </div>
